<<<api>>>: Iterator.next
<<<code>>>: 
```java
import java.util.*;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<String> list = new ArrayList<>();
        list.add("First");
        list.add("Second");
        list.add("Third");

        String firstElementList = list.iterator().next();
        System.out.println("First element of the list: " + firstElementList);

        Set<String> set = new HashSet<>();
        set.add("First");
        set.add("Second");
        set.add("Third");

        String firstElementSet = set.iterator().next();
        System.out.println("First element of the set: " + firstElementSet);
    }
}
```
<<<explanation>>>: In the given code, we first create a List and a Set with some elements. To get the first element of the List or Set, we use the iterator() method to get an Iterator and then call the next() method on the Iterator. The next() method returns the next element in the iteration. For a List, the first element is the one that was added first. For a Set, since it does not maintain any order, the "first" element can be any of the elements.
